Gemini said
Since you're on Arch Linux, you're likely running Kanata either as a systemd user service or manually via the terminal.

Here is how to check the logs for both scenarios:

1. If running as a Systemd User Service
If you set up a service file in ~/.config/systemd/user/kanata.service, use journalctl with the --user flag. This is the most common way to debug "it didn't work" failures.

View recent logs:

Bash
journalctl --user -u kanata.service -e
Follow logs in real-time (best for debugging config changes):

Bash
journalctl --user -u kanata.service -f
Check the current status/errors:

Bash
systemctl --user status kanata.service
2. If running manually in the Terminal
If you are starting Kanata by running the binary directly, it should output logs to your terminal (stdout/stderr). If you need more detail to find a syntax error in your .kbd file, use the debug flags:

Run with Debug logging:

Bash
kanata --cfg /path/to/your/config.kbd --debug
Only check config syntax (without starting the driver):

Bash
kanata --cfg /path/to/your/config.kbd --check
Common "Didn't Work" Reasons on Arch
If the logs show a Permission Denied (os error 13), it’s usually one of two things:

Missing Group Permissions: Your user needs to be in the input and uinput groups.

Bash
sudo usermod -aG input,uinput $USER
(Note: You must log out and back in for this to take effect.)

Missing uinput Module: The kernel module might not be loaded.

Bash
sudo modprobe uinput
To make it permanent, create /etc/modules-load.d/uinput.conf and just put the word uinput inside.

Udev Rules: Ensure you have a udev rule for /dev/uinput. You can usually find the recommended rule in the Kanata GitHub documentation.

